          'school': 'Harvard University',
          'major': 'Neuroscience/Global Health and Health Policy',
          'experience': 'Lee Ann Song is a 22-year-old ABC (American-born Chinese) who graduated from Harvard in May 2015 with a degree in Neuroscience and a minor in Global Health and Health Policy. She began working for an organization called Ivy League International during her junior year of college and has been helping Chinese high school students get into well-ranked U.S. colleges since 2013. ',
          'characteristic': "Even though I was a pre-medical student at Harvard, my greatest strength has always been in writing. I began writing on a competitive creative writing team in middle school that won our state championship, and I have since developed my argumentative and academic writing skills. My high school research has been published in the scientific journal, Neuro-oncology, and my college thesis contributed to a developmental psychology article published in Psychological Science. During our mandatory freshmen writing seminar at Harvard, my writing was selected to be published as an example for incoming students. <br>I am proof that you do not have to be a perfect student to get into a top university—writing a compelling personal statement can help your application tremendously. Upon graduation, I had the opportunity to read my admissions file and I learned that the maturity and self-awareness I demonstrated in my essay impressed my reviewers enough to give me high recommendations for admission. <br>I have worked closely with Harvard interviewers and friends in the Harvard admissions office to understand what admissions committees look for in applicants. Though I have a passion for writing and helping students write essays, my real hope is to take a more holistic approach--to help students not just present the best version of themselves, but to actually be the best version of themselves. Because I had grown up always doing what others thought was best for me, I had to discover for myself what my passions were at Harvard. I found that I loved playing cello in the Harvard-Radcliffe Orchestra, volunteering at Massachusetts General Hospital through an organization called Health Leads, and traveling to developing countries to teach music and develop public health programs. The words on Harvard gate read, 'Enter to grow in wisdom,' and on the other side, 'depart to better serve thy country and thy kind.' These words inspired me to use my talent for writing to help other deserving students receive the kind of education that I received. <br>Last year, I wrote a personal statement that beat nearly 300 other Harvard applicants and was selected to win the honorable Michael C. Rockefeller post-graduate travel fellowship. I have spent the past year traveling and learning in South America. Now I am conversationally fluent in three languages--English, Mandarin, and Spanish. This experience has given me the opportunity to learn about music improvisation, holistic medicine, and some other things I have always wanted to learn, including martial arts, cross-fit, hip hop dancing, computer science, personal and small business finance, jazz, and cooking. Most importantly, I have found a sense of self-worth not rooted in external validation, and I have rediscovered a genuine excitement to learn without fear of failure. It would be my honor to help you do the same. Getting into a respectable university will serve you well in life, but what will serve you better is your character, grit, and a strong sense of self! ",
